#: ../../manual/sculpt_paint/painting/weight_paint/introduction.rst:97
msgid "Weight Painting for Bones"
msgstr "Pintura de pesos de influência para ossos"

#: ../../manual/sculpt_paint/painting/weight_paint/introduction.rst:99
msgid "This is one of the main uses of weight painting. When a bone moves, vertices around the joint should move as well, but just a little, to mimic the stretching of the skin around the joint. Use a \"light\" weight (10 - 40%) paint on the vertices around the joint so that they move a little when the bone rotates. While there are ways to automatically assign weights to an armature (see the :doc:`Armature section </rigging/index>`), you can do this manually. To do this from scratch, refer to the process below. To modify automatically assigned weights, jump into the middle of the process where noted:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/sculpt_paint/painting/weight_paint/introduction.rst:109
msgid "Create an armature."
msgstr "Crie uma armação de ossos."

#: ../../manual/sculpt_paint/painting/weight_paint/introduction.rst:110
msgid "Create a mesh that will be deformed when the armature's bone(s) move."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/sculpt_paint/painting/weight_paint/introduction.rst:111
msgid "With the mesh selected, create an *Armature* modifier for your mesh (located in the Properties editor, *Modifiers* tab). Enter the name of the armature."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/sculpt_paint/painting/weight_paint/introduction.rst:115
msgid "Pick up here for modifying automatically assigned weights."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/sculpt_paint/painting/weight_paint/introduction.rst:117
msgid "Select the armature in 3D View, and bring the armature to *Pose Mode* with :kbd:`Ctrl-Tab`, or the 3D View header mode selector."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/sculpt_paint/painting/weight_paint/introduction.rst:119
msgid "Select a desired bone in the armature."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/sculpt_paint/painting/weight_paint/introduction.rst:120
msgid "Select your mesh with :kbd:`RMB` and change immediately to *Weight Paint Mode*. The mesh will be colored according to the weight (degree) that the selected bone movement affects the mesh. Initially, it will be all blue (no effect)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/sculpt_paint/painting/weight_paint/introduction.rst:123
msgid "Weight paint to your heart's content. The mesh around the bone itself should be red (generally) and fade out through the rainbow to blue for vertices farther away from the bone."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/sculpt_paint/painting/weight_paint/introduction.rst:127
msgid "You may select a different bone with :kbd:`RMB` while weight painting, provided the armature was left in *Pose Mode* as described above. This will activate the vertex group sharing the name with the selected bone, and display related weights. If the mesh skins the bones, you will not be able to see the bones because the mesh is painted. If so, turn on *X-Ray* view (Properties Editor, *Armature* tab)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/sculpt_paint/painting/weight_paint/introduction.rst:134
msgid "If you paint on the mesh, a vertex group is created for the bone. If you paint on vertices outside the group, the painted vertices are automatically added to the vertex group."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/sculpt_paint/painting/weight_paint/introduction.rst:138
msgid "If you have a symmetrical mesh and a symmetrical armature you can use the option *X-Mirror*. Then the mirrored groups with the mirrored weights are automatically created."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/sculpt_paint/painting/weight_paint/introduction.rst:144
msgid "Weight Painting for Particles"
msgstr "Pintura de pesos de influência para partículas"

#: ../../manual/sculpt_paint/painting/weight_paint/introduction.rst:148
msgid "Weight painted particle emission."
msgstr "Emissão de partículas através de pesos de influência."

#: ../../manual/sculpt_paint/painting/weight_paint/introduction.rst:150
#, python-format
msgid "Faces or vertices with zero weight generate no particles. A weight of 0.1 will result in 10% of the amounts of particles. This option \"conserves\" the total indicated number of particles, adjusting the distributions so that the proper weights are achieved while using the actual number of particles called for. Use this to make portions of your mesh hairier than others by weight painting a vertex group, and then calling out the name of the vertex group in the *VGroup:* field (*Particles* panel, *Object* tab)."
msgstr ""

